(21, '<p>Silver &quot;Aladdins Lamp&quot; Teapot</p>\r\r\n', '1294639200', '0000-00-00', '1787', '26', '16', '13', '17', '1000', 0, 'Yes', '1', '<p>Fluted sides and spout. Engraved with pendent floral sprays, ivory handle, shaped oval pedestal foot with crowned lion&#39;s head erased crest. This piece by William Plummer is unusual as he is famous for using saw-cut piercings in most of his wor', '<p>W.P into a chamfered indented rectangle, William Plummer, entered 1755, London 1787 hallmark. William Plummer was one of the Silversmiths whose work became very popular during the middle to end of the 18th century. Bibliography: Christie&#39;s Int', '300', 'GBP', 'GBP', 'Shelf 17', 'B', '', '<p>A GEORGE III SILVER &quot;ALADDIN&#39;S LAMP&quot; TEAPOT MARK OF WILLIAM PLUMMER, LONDON, 1787 FLUTED SIDES AND SPOUT, ENGRAVED WITH PENDENT FLORAL SPRAYS, IVORY HANDLE AND FINIAL, SHAPED OVAL PEDESTAL FOOT WITH CROWNED LION&#39;S HEAD ERASED CRE', 'Active', '', '0', '', '', '', '', 'Yes'),
(22, '<p>Octagonal Paper Scroll Tea Caddy</p>\r\r\n', '1273986000', '0000-00-00', 'C 1790', '15', '13.5', '10', '22.01', '1800', 0, 'Yes', '2', '<p>This is an example of a tea caddy that would have been painstakingly decorated at home. Wooden tea caddies with a raised framework were made by cabinet makers specifically to take filigree paperwork, a popular pastime during the 18th century. They', '<p>Bibliography: Christie&#39;s Interiors Style &amp; Spirit Catalogue, Sale 5702, London, 18 May 2010, lot 4.</p>\r\r\n', '528.75', 'GBP', 'GBP', 'Shelf 5', 'B', '', '<p>Lot Description A GEORGE III OCTAGONAL PAPER-SCROLL TEA CADDY CIRCA 1790 The glazed panels with mica ground, the front panel with a painted view of a waterfall 5&frac14; in. (13.3 cm.) high; 5 7/8 in. (15 cm.) wide; 4 in. (10 cm.) deep</p>\r\r\n', 'Active', '', '0', '', '', '', '', 'Yes'),
(23, '<p>Edwardian Tortoiseshell Tea Caddy</p>\r\r\n', '1273986000', '0000-00-00', '1901-1910', '0', '12.5', '0', '0', '2200', 0, 'No', '3', '<p>A dark tortoiseshell Tea Caddy. Tortoiseshell is made of two proteins keratin and chitin. This means that with heat the shell can be moulded into various shapes, yet high heats will darken the shell making the desirable markings less distinct. Thi', '<p>Bibliography: Christie&#39;s Interiors Style &amp; Spirit Catalogue, Sale 5702, London, 18 May 2010, lot 1.</p>\r\r\n', '646.25', 'GBP', 'GBP', 'Shelf 5', 'B', '', '<p>Lot Description AN EDWARDIAN TORTOISESHELL TEA CADDY EARLY 20TH CENTURY Of hexagonal bombe form, the interior with ivory banding and caddy spoon 5 in. (12.5 cm.) high</p>\r\r\n', 'Active', '', '0', '', '', '', '', 'Yes'),
